% Key PDD CLI features relevant for completion (including recent updates):
% Global Options:
%   --force: Overwrite existing files.
%   --strength <float>: Set AI model strength.
%   --temperature <float>: Set AI model temperature.
%   --verbose: Increase output verbosity.
%   --quiet: Decrease output verbosity.
%   --time <float>: Specifies a timeout duration in seconds for the operation (e.g., --time 0.5 or --time 10).
%   --provider <name>: Pin local-mode model selection to a single provider (also reads PDD_PROVIDER). Accepts a canonical alias (``openai``, ``azure_openai``, ``vertex_ai``, ``azure_ai``, ``anthropic``, ``gemini``, ``github_copilot``, ``openrouter``, ``perplexity``), the exact CSV provider name (case-insensitive), or an unambiguous substring. ``--provider`` must appear in the global options list so it is offered alongside other globals. The completion script must additionally: (a) when the previous token is ``--provider``, suggest the canonical alias values above and NOT fall through to global options or subcommand options; (b) treat ALL value-taking global options as transparent when scanning for the active subcommand. The subcommand-detection scan must consume two tokens for every value-taking global option (``--provider``, ``--strength``, ``--time``, ``--temperature``, ``--output-cost``, ``--context``) and one token for every flag-only global option, so invocations like ``pdd --strength 0.7 generate <TAB>``, ``pdd --temperature 0 generate <TAB>``, and ``pdd --provider openai generate <TAB>`` all locate ``generate`` as the active subcommand and offer its options. Skipping only ``--provider`` is insufficient — the previous implementation regressed when other value-taking global options preceded the subcommand.
%   (Other global options as per the full README.md)
%
% Commands:
%   generate, example, test, preprocess, fix, split, etc. (as per the full README.md)
%   Each command may have its own specific options.
%   Include `checkup` with all README-documented checkup options, including recovery (`--start-step`), PR mode (`--pr`, `--issue`) and review-loop mode (`--review-loop`, `--review-only`, `--reviewer`, `--fixer`, `--reviewer-fallback`, role/limit/status flags). The review-loop status-handling flags include `--continue-on-reviewer-limit` (report provider/rate/timeout failures as degraded) and `--fallback-reviewer-on-failure` (promote the fixer to a fallback reviewer when the primary ends in failed/missing). The deterministic-gate flags (issue #1092) include `--no-gates` (disable gate enforcement), `--gate-timeout SECONDS` (per-gate wall-clock cap, default 60), and the repeatable `--gate-allow CMD` (forward-compatibility hook for opting extra gate names into discovery).

% The bash completion script (pdd_completion.sh) should meet the following requirements:
%   - Support all PDD CLI commands and their respective options, including global options.
%   - Provide auto-completion for filenames where appropriate (e.g., for prompt files, code files).
%   - Auto-complete command names.
%   - Auto-complete option names (both global and command-specific).
%   - The completion for the global option '--time' should anticipate a numerical (float) value as its argument and not suggest other options or filenames at that point.
%   - The script must not require the installation of the 'bash-completion' package and should be self-contained.

% Ensure the completion logic correctly identifies the current command context to offer relevant options and arguments.
